<p>
<p>A researcher wants to know whether children who frequently use headphones have worse hearing than children who never use headphones. The higher the score on a hearing test, the better the hearing. The reliability of a hearing test is .81. In the table below, the means and standard deviations of the two groups are given. What would be the effect size Cohen’s d, <span class="math inline">\(d_{XT}\)</span>, if the hearing test were perfectly reliable?</p>
<table class="table_shade">
<thead>
<tr class="header">
<th style="text-align: left;">Condition</th>
<th style="text-align: left;">Mean</th>
<th style="text-align: left;">SD</th>
<th style="text-align: left;">N</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr class="odd">
<td style="text-align: left;">Headphones</td>
<td style="text-align: left;">10</td>
<td style="text-align: left;">2</td>
<td style="text-align: left;">30</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td style="text-align: left;">No headphones</td>
<td style="text-align: left;">11.25</td>
<td style="text-align: left;">3</td>
<td style="text-align: left;">30</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</p>]]></text>
</questiontext>
<generalfeedback format="html">
<text><![CDATA[<p>
<p>First you use:
<span class="math inline">\(d_{xO} = (x̄_{O1} -x̄_{O2}) \div √ ((S^2_{O1}+S^2_{O2}) \div 2)\)</span> to calculate <span class="math inline">\(d_{Xo}\)</span>.</p>
<p>This makes <span class="math inline">\((11.25 - 10) \div √((9 + 4) \div 2)=1.25 \div √6.5 = (1.25 ) \div (2.5495) = 0.490\)</span>.</p>
<p>Then you use:
<span class="math inline">\(d_{X_O} = d_{X_T} \times √R_{XX}\)</span></p>
<p>To calculate <span class="math inline">\(d_{X_T}\)</span>, this makes <span class="math inline">\(0.409 \div √0.81 = 0.409 \div 0.9 = 0.545\)</span>.</p>
</p>]]></text>
